<p><i><b>Azadirachta indica</b></i> (commonly known as <b>neem</b>, <b>nimtree</b> and <b>Indian lilac</b><sup id="cite_ref-GRIN_2-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GRIN-2">[2]</a></sup>) is a tree in the <a href="/wiki/Mahogany" title="Mahogany">mahogany</a> family <a href="/wiki/Meliaceae" title="Meliaceae">Meliaceae</a>. It is one of two species in the genus <i><a href="/wiki/Azadirachta" title="Azadirachta">Azadirachta</a></i>, and is native to the <a href="/wiki/Indian_subcontinent" title="Indian subcontinent">Indian subcontinent</a>, i.e. <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nepal" title="Nepal">Nepal</a>, <a href="/wiki/Pakistan" title="Pakistan">Pakistan</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bangladesh" title="Bangladesh">Bangladesh</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sri_Lanka" title="Sri Lanka">Sri Lanka</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Maldives" title="Maldives">Maldives</a>. It typically is grown in <a href="/wiki/Tropical" class="mw-redirect" title="Tropical">tropical</a> and semi-tropical regions. Neem trees now also grow in islands located in the southern part of <a href="/wiki/Iran" title="Iran">Iran</a>. Its fruits and seeds are the source of <a href="/wiki/Neem_oil" title="Neem oil">neem oil</a>.</p>
